count of the contradictory character of colonial government and examines the cultural nationalism of Negritude as a multifaceted movement rooted in an alternative black public sphere. He argues that interwar France must be understood as an imperial nation-state—an integrated sociopolitical system that linked a parliamentary republic to an administrative empire. An interdisciplinary study of colonial modernity combining French history, colonial studies, and social theory, The French Imperial Nation-State will compel readers to revise conventional assumptions about the distinctions between republicanism and racism, metropolitan and colonial societies, and national and transnational processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aAfricanszFrance. 0aBlacksxRace identityzAfrica, WestxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlackszFrance. 0aNationalismzAfrica, WestxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226773858423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226773858.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles